==English== [[File:Britannica Macropaedia.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Volumes 21–24 of ''Britannica'''s ''[[w:Macropædia|Macropædia]]'' (covering topics from ''India'' to ''Norway'') in the [[w:Deutsches Museum|Deutsches Museum]]'s library.]]
[[File:Göttingen-SUB-Encyclopedia.Americana.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Volumes 5–12 of the ''Encyclopedia Americana'' (covering topics from ''Bulgaria'' to ''Goethals'') in the SUB Library at the University of Göttingen, Germany.]]
===Alternative forms=== * {{alt|en|encyclopaedia||Commonwealth}} * {{alt|en|encyclopædia||dated}}
===Etymology=== {{root|en|ine-pro|*peh₂w-}} {{etymon|en|id=reference work|:bor|NL.:encyclopaedīa<id:encyclopedia>|tree=1}} {{bor+|en|NL.|encyclopēdīa, [[encyclopaedia|encyclopaedīa]]|t=general education}}, a [[univerbation|univerbated]] form of {{der|en|grc-koi|ἐγκύκλιος παιδείᾱ|t=education in the circle of arts and sciences}}, from {{der|en|grc|ἐγκύκλιος||[[circular]]}} + {{m|grc|παιδείᾱ||[[childrearing]]; [[education]]}} ([[q.v.]]). Nearly all modern English usage of the word was influenced by the scope and format of the {{der|en|fr|-}} ''{{w|Encyclopédie}}'' by {{w|Diderot}} [[et al.]] (see quotation).
===Pronunciation=== * {{IPA|en|/ənˌsəɪ.kləˈpi.di.ə/|a=Canada}} * {{IPA|en|/ɪnˌsaɪ.kləˈpi(ː).dɪə/|a=UK}} * {{IPA|en|/ɪnˌsaɪ.kləˈpi(ː).di.ə/|a=US}} * {{audio|en|en-us-encyclopedia.ogg|a=US}} * {{rhymes|en|iːdiə|s=6}} * {{hyphenation|en|en|cy|clo|pe|di|a}}
===Noun=== {{en-noun|s|encyclopediae|encyclopediæ}}
# {{senseid|en|Q5292}}A [[comprehensive]] [[reference work]] (often spanning several printed volumes) with articles (usually arranged in alphabetical order, or sometimes arranged by category) on a range of [[subjects]], sometimes general, sometimes limited to a particular field. #: {{ux|en|I only use the library for the '''encyclopedia''', as we’ve got most other books here.}} #: {{ux|en|My old '''encyclopedia''' has been gathering dust on the shelf for the past decade.}} #* {{quote-book|en |author=Jean-Baptiste le Rond d'Alembert |title=Encyclopédie ou Dictionnaire raisonné des sciences, des arts et des métiers |title2=The '''Encyclopedia''' of Diderot & d'Alembert Collaborative Translation Project |translators=Richard N. Schwab; Walter E. Rex. |publisher2=Michigan Publishing, University of Michigan Library |location=Paris |location2=[[w:Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor]] |year=1751 |format2=Web |url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/d/did/ |volume=1 |chapter=Discours Préliminaire |chapter2=Preliminary Discourse |chapterurl=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=did;rgn=main;view=text;idno=did2222.0001.083 |pages=1–45 |date2=April 18, 2009 |text=The '''Encyclopedia''' which we are presenting to the public is, as its title declares, the work of a society of men of letters. Were we not of their number, we might venture to affirm that they are all favorably known or worthy of being so.}} #* {{quote-book|en <!-- This title is in New Latin (see [[encyclopaedia#Latin]]), not English, so we don't embolden it --> |title=Encyclopedia Americana |year=1920 |editor=[[w:George Edwin Rines|George Edwin Rines]] |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Encyclopedia_Americana_(1920) |volume_plain=Volume X: Egusquiza – Falsetto |volumeurl=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Encyclopedia_Americana_(1920)/Volume_X:_Egusquiza_-_Falsetto |section='''Encyclopædia''' <!-- article name --> |sectionurl=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Encyclopedia_Americana_(1920)/Encyclop%C3%A6dia ... [truncated]
